New files to build (same structural discipline as your existing code)
csa.sv — Carry-Save Adder. SRT-4's inner loop needs to add three values (partial remainder sum, carry, and ±divisor) without waiting for carry propagation. CSA does it in O(1) with just full-adder primitives — you'd build it from your existing gate primitives exactly like adder.sv but with a generate loop producing sum/carry outputs separately. No ripple.
lut_quotient.sv — The heart of SRT-4. In each iteration you look at the top ~4-6 bits of the partial remainder and select a quotient digit from {−2, −1, 0, +1, +2}. This is a pure combinational lookup table — a big always_comb case statement. It's the piece that makes SRT-4 fast compared to restoring or non-restoring division.
shifter.sv — A proper n-bit left shifter (your existing lshift.sv is hardwired 8→9-bit). For SRT-4 you need to normalize the operands first (shift until the MSB is known). Build it as a parameterized iterative shift using your register.sv shift capability, controlled by a small counter.
add_sub.sv — Thin wrapper around adder.sv that wires in the XOR+cin trick you already use in Booth to select add vs subtract based on a control bit. Almost no new logic.
logic_unit.sv — Wires AND, OR, XOR, NOT from gates.sv behind a 2-bit opcode mux. Pure combinational, no FSM needed.
srt4_div.sv + cu_srt4.sv — The big one. Structurally mirrors booth.sv/cu_booth.sv: datapath instantiates CSA, registers (for partial remainder sum/carry, quotient accumulation), the LUT, and the shifter; the FSM controls the pipeline of NORMALIZE → ITERATE (select digit → CSA update → shift) → CONVERT (on-the-fly quotient conversion from redundant to binary) → OUTPUT. The FSM states map cleanly to your existing cu_booth style.
alu_top.sv + cu_alu.sv — Top-level glues all units together. cu_alu decodes the opcode (ADD, SUB, MUL, DIV, AND, OR, XOR, NOT) and issues an enable to the right sub-unit, then waits for its done signal. alu_top routes the inbus/outbus through tri-state buffers, exactly like booth.sv already does for its own shared bus.
